Derbyshire, England":"Hathersage, Derbyshire, England"},"nl":{"1348–1410":"1348–1410","1348–1380":"1348–1380","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1368–Female":"1368–Overleden","1370–1459":"1370–1459","1318–1385":"1318–1385","1323–Female":"1323–Overleden","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","after 1368":"na 1368","1459":"1459","1348":"1348","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1318":"1318","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Hope, Derbyshire, England":"Hope, Derbyshire, England","Ireland":"Ierland","England":"England","Hathersage, Derbyshire, England":"Hathersage, Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"1348–1410":"1348–1410","1348–1380":"1348–1380","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1368–Female":"1368–Deceased","1370–1459":"1370–1459","1318–1385":"1318–1385","1323–Female":"1323–Deceased","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","after 1368":"after 1368","1459":"1459","1348":"1348","1368":"1368","1323":"1323","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1318":"1318","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Hope, Derbyshire, England":"Hope, Derbyshire, England","Ireland":"Ireland","England":"England","Hathersage, Derbyshire, England":"Hathersage, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Eyre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Ayer  .","History: This name was that of a historically prominent family in Galway (Ireland) since the 1650s."],"variants":[{"name":"Ayer","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>eir</i>, <i>eyr</i> ‘heir’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>heyr</i>, Old French <i>(h)eir</i>, Latin <i>heres</i>). Forms such as <i>Richard le Heyer</i> were frequent in Middle English, denoting a man who was well known to be the heir to the main property in a particular locality, either one who had already inherited or one with great expectations.","English: from the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Aier</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Agihari</i>).","English: variant of   Hair  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Eyre was born in 1348, in Hope, Derbyshire, England, his father, Nicholas Eyre, was 30 and his mother, Joan De Padley, was 25. He married Annabella Archer in 1368, in Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 da